Likely root cause: a check-then-act race around token expiry.

At `src/auth/rate_limiter.ts:42`, if the code does something like:

```ts
if (token.isExpired()) {
  refreshToken()
}
```

then two concurrent refresh requests can both read the same expired state before either one records that refresh is already in progress. Each request then schedules its own refresh work.

The fix is usually to make refresh scheduling single-flight:

```ts
let refreshPromise: Promise<Token> | null = null

function getFreshToken() {
  if (!token.isExpired()) return Promise.resolve(token)

  if (!refreshPromise) {
    refreshPromise = refreshToken().finally(() => {
      refreshPromise = null
    })
  }

  return refreshPromise
}
```

Key points to verify later:

- Whether the “refresh in progress” marker is set synchronously before any `await`.
- Whether the expired-token check and refresh scheduling happen in separate async turns.
- Whether failed refreshes correctly clear the marker.
- Whether callers share the same limiter/token state instance.
- Whether the rate limiter increments or queues work before deduplication.

That failure mode is plausible if the mutex protects the wrong identity or too broad a section.

A mutex can still allow duplicate refreshes when:

- The lock is created inside the request handler, controller, middleware, or short-lived service instance.
- Each concurrent request gets a different handler/service instance.
- The lock key is global or absent, but the token state is actually per tenant.
- The expired-token check happens before acquiring the lock.
- The refresh-in-progress marker is stored on an object that is not shared across requests.
- Horizontal workers/processes each have their own in-memory mutex.
- Tenant context is resolved after lock acquisition, so different tenants or instances do not converge on the same synchronization primitive.

The classic broken shape is:

```ts
async function handleRefresh(req) {
  const mutex = new Mutex()

  if (isExpired(req.tenantId)) {
    await mutex.runExclusive(async () => {
      await refresh(req.tenantId)
    })
  }
}
```

This serializes nothing useful because every request owns a different mutex.

A less obvious broken shape is:

```ts
class AuthHandler {
  private mutex = new Mutex()
}
```

If the framework constructs `AuthHandler` per request, per route invocation, per tenant shard, or per worker, concurrent refreshes may not share the same lock.

The lock should be scoped to the shared resource being protected: usually `(tenantId, auth provider, token subject)` rather than the handler instance. Even then, the double-check must happen inside the lock:

```ts
await lockForTenant(tenantId).runExclusive(async () => {
  if (isExpired(tenantId)) {
    await refresh(tenantId)
  }
})
```

Otherwise both requests can observe expiry before serialization and both decide refresh is needed.
